column32: This submission corrects an error in the original submission dated July 12, 2019: the sole reporting entity for this incident is Attunity, Inc. This is not a notice of any kind of systemic data breach of Attunity. Rather, Attunity discovered that its back-ups of ex-employee data were made potentially accessible to the public due to an inadvertent misconfiguration of several AWS S3 buckets. Attunity swiftly remedied the situation by closing off public access to the data. Attunity launched a forensic investigation with the assistance of two third-party IT security firms to determine the content of the data. At this point, the investigation is complete.  All affected individuals have been notified and offered 2 years of Equifax ID Patrol® credit monitoring and identity theft monitoring services free of charge, even though there is no indication that any of the potentially exposed information was accessed by a malicious third party.  Therefore, there is no substantial risk of identity theft or fraud, and it is unlikely that any personal information will be misused due to the misconfiguration.

column32: On July 24, 2019, we discovered that the login point for users on the Niche.com website was subject to an automated attack. The attack attempted to gain access to Niche user accounts using username and password pairs from externally available sources. While our investigation found no evidence that user account information was compromised or changed, there were successful logins detected for certain Niche users from a source believed to be a part of the attack. We promptly investigated the scope of the attack and disabled potentially compromised passwords. Though we did not find any evidence that any account information was collected from the users following the unauthorized login, we locked user accounts and prompted users to reset passwords out of an abundance of caution.

column32: A recent software update to Maine Revenue Services' EZ Pay System allowed a taxpayer with the same first and last name of another taxpayer (i.e., the affected taxpayer) to view certain account information of the affected taxpayer (including name, SSN, and partial bank routing information).  The taxpayer contacted Maine Revenue Services believing there was an account error.  Maine Revenue Services identified and corrected the software error, which was due the taxpayers having the same first and last name as well as similar user names in the EZ Pay System.  Maine Revenue Services attempted to contact the affected taxpayer by phone to explain the issue.  However, Maine Revenue Services then issued a letter to the affected taxpayer on June 10, 2019, explaining the situation and offering identity protection services.  Maine Revenue Services, along with the Office of Information Technology, conducted a comprehensive investigation to identify any other possible taxpayers who could have been affected by the software error (i.e., who met the specific criteria of having the same first and last names and similar user names in the EZ Pay System).  Maine Revenue Services has no evidence or reports that anyone else has been affected but identified 87 possibly affected taxpayers who met the limited criteria.  Out of an abundance of caution, Maine Revenue Services mailed notification letters to the potentially affected 87 taxpayers explaining that their personal information may have been inadvertently viewed by another taxpayer and that the temporary system error was corrected.

column25: A&A was notified of suspicious activity on August 17, 2018 and immediately launched a forensic investigation.  The forensic investigation concluded on December 7, 2018, revealing a breach impacting Maine residents.
column40: Once A&A’s forensic investigation revealed a breach impacting Maine residents, and had restored the integrity and security of the impacted systems, A&A prepared to notify those impacted individuals. Notifications to the impacted individuals in Maine were sent by U.S. Mail on January 9, 2019.
